Citations
Date:  0/0/1935
Source:  Slang Today
Author:  PARTRIDGE
Vol / Page:  286
Edition:
Quote:  [The] following [was] employed by those who served in the [Great] War ... <i>give someone a pop</i>, to have a `go' at, especially in fisticuffs or in shooting with a rifle or machine-gun; <i>Ibid.</i> 287 He absolutely dropped his bundle, and, to make matters worse, I had started off with a duck's breakfast, but I saw a cookhouse and decided to give it a pop for a binder.
